  "summary": "Keyword co-occurrence in bundled CLI/server code requires human review",
  "details": "Pattern matches fired across multiple bundled files (dist/cli.cjs, dist/cli.js, dist/index.cjs, dist/index.js, dist/server/index.{cjs,js}, dist/widget.global.js) on co-occurrence of Buffer.from(..., 'base64') with.toString(), and on the strings 'ping' and 'POST'. These are common primitives in legitimate developer tooling (base64 decoding of assets/tokens for HTTP auth, ping endpoints, REST POST handlers) and are not by themselves evidence of exfiltration. No hardcoded attacker C2 endpoint, credential-path enumeration, browser/wallet store access, or install-time lifecycle execution was identified. package.json lifecycle hooks were not observed to invoke any of the flagged code paths automatically. Without traced execution showing installer-side data flowing to an attacker-controlled destination, the structural fingerprints required for a block are not satisfied. Routing for human review so a reviewer can confirm whether the POST destinations and base64 payloads in the bundled CLI/server are documented vendor endpoints or something else.",
